18 2021-03-21 seizure, unresponsive to stimuli Patient received vaccine in the AM of 3/16/21. Patient was in his usual state of health when he wen... Read more
Close
Patient received vaccine in the AM of 3/16/21. Patient was in his usual state of health when he went to bed the evening of 3/16/21. He ate dinner normally and his PD was started as usual. There were no overnight complications with his PD and he got up shortly before 8 AM. Mom reports the dialysate from his bag was clear and normal and none of his dwell was retained. She heard a loud thud from the bathroom around 8 AM and the patient was found by his mother having generalized convulsions (bilateral upper and lower extremities) and he appeared to be foaming at the mouth. He did not respond to her and she called 911. The seizure stopped by the time EMS arrived and his initial GCS was 12, and 15 by the time they started transport. He had another seizure en route around 9:30 AM and was given 2.5 mg versed and required bagging. Patient was loaded with Keppra and now has been on maintenance Keppra. Patient has not suffered any additional seizures and is currently undergoing an extensive workup by inpatient neurology team. Vaccine adverse effect currently remains on the differential for inciting event leading to seizure however additional labs are pending to rule out other causes (eg. viruses causing PML). Patient was also diagnosed with multifocal pneumonia and started on antibiotics at time of admission.

18 2021-04-07 seizure Patient at Vaccination table, just received dose of vaccine when patient's arm went limp. Also devel... Read more
Close
Patient at Vaccination table, just received dose of vaccine when patient's arm went limp. Also developed generalized weakness. Mother stood in front of him and held his head with both hands. Patient then passed out with eyes rolling in back of head. Also had convulsions for a few seconds that mimicked seizure. Patient soon became alert. Vitals obtained with BP 92/52, HR 34, O2 96% on RA. Patient also diaphoretic to touch. EMS activated and arrived at 1:30pm. Placed in reclining wheelchair and taken to private area. Started to feel better after given cold water. Suggested ER due to having seizure first time. Declined ambulance but mother will take to ER in private car. Patient and mother left with no further incident.
18 2021-04-08 seizure, feeling cold Perfectly healthy, fit, thin 18 year old young man with no allergies and no previous reactions to ... Read more
Close
Perfectly healthy, fit, thin 18 year old young man with no allergies and no previous reactions to vaccines or medications... immediately upon receiving J&J injection his eyes rolled back into his head and he was unconscious for two to three minutes, then in and out of consciousness for another eight to ten minutes. He convulsed for around ten seconds after about two minutes of being unconscious. Four to five healthcare workers attended to him, asking him to "stay with us." They called an ambulance, and the medics monitored him for awhile. Heart rate dropped to 34 bpm, clothing drenched with perspiration. Blood sugar was slightly low, although he had eaten a late brunch of two fried eggs, sourdough toast and fruit salad. The last thing he remembers is a cold sensation shooting down his arm and into his left hand. He tried to talk to say he wasn't feeling well, but he couldn't form the words, so he raised his arm and then fainted. He felt generally unwell the rest of the day, and today he is still not fully recovered.
18 2021-04-09 feeling cold, weakness, cold sweat, feeling hot After a few hours, developed a low grade headache and some soreness at the injection site. About tw... Read more
Close
After a few hours, developed a low grade headache and some soreness at the injection site. About two hours later I started getting extremely cold, despite the temperature in the mid-high 70s. I covered up under blankets. I began feeling very tired and a general sick feeling. After about an hour and a half of progressively worse chills and cold sweat, I began to get very very hot and removed all blankets and eventually clothes. I took my temperature, which was at 102 f. At this point I drank some water and Gatorade and waited for it to pass. I also noticed that my Apple Watch heart rate detection was saying my heart rate was in the high 90s to low 100s despite me just laying in bed. This was alarming because my typical resting heart rate is in the low 60s. About two hours later I felt well enough to at least brush my teeth, but upon standing up was greeted with an extreme feeling of weakness and dizziness and it was hard to keep myself up right. I eventually was able to fall asleep, and upon waking up, felt better, but still not great. My heart rate was more normal at this point, I no longer had chills or a fever, but still had a headache and soreness across my body, worst at the injection site.

He was very cold and the headache did not let up after several hours. Eventually he had a bout of sweats and he reports he was soaked. In the morning, at 8 am the headache was still severe...was sensitive to noise, light and touch. He was given 2 extra strength Tylenol at 8 and then 2 Advil at 10am, which finally began to reduce symptoms. He was not hungry, felt weak, and finally by late night he was feeling better. In the morning on Saturday he awoke with a swollen left eye and blood shot in that eye.

The batch number was not reported and has been requested. No concomitant medications were reported. On 08-APR-2021 around 19:30, the patient experienced vomiting, had fever, shakes and complained of numb legs and was unable to feel them. He was instructed by his physician to go to the nearest Emergency room (ER). The patient visited emergency room or department and physician office for treatment of the events. He went to ER but was unable to walk at that time and was carried in. The patient was evaluated, had normal chest X-ray (CXR), temperature up to 104, had emesis, underwent rapid covid test which was negative. He was given intravenous (IV) fluids, Zofran, Tylenol and was discharged home. It was reported that the patient was doing better but with continued tiredness, weakness, his legs were feeling better, temperature was down, coherent and was tolerating fluids. Laboratory data included: Body temperature (NR: not provided) 104, COVID-19 antigen test (NR: not provided) Negative, and CXR (NR: not provided) Normal. Treatment medications (dates unspecified) included: paracetamol, and ondansetron. The action taken with covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s was not applicable. The patient was recovering from vomiting/emesis, fever, shakes, and legs numb, had not recovered from weakness, and tiredness, and the outcome of unable to walk was not reported. This report was serious (Other Medically Important Condition).; Sender's Comments: V0: 20210420466-covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s-vomiting/emesis, shakes, legs numb, unable to walk. This event(s) is considered unassessable. The event(s) has a compatible/suggestive temporal relationship, is unlabeled, and has unknown scientific plausibility. There is no information on any other factors potentially associated with the event(s). 20210420466-covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s-Fever. Within a minute of receiving the vaccine, patient slumped back in the chair, head back, eyes open. He was unresponsive and shaking in the chair. After about 20 seconds he came to and leaned forward but wasn't oriented to time and place. As I was talking to him, trying to assess his breathing, he slumped back in the chair and began shaking much more violently. I asked the store director to call EMS at that point, I took his mask off at that point to better assess his breathing. After about 15 seconds, he came to again. At that point, I had him lean forward with his elbows on his knees, and he didn't lose conciousness after that. I took his blood pressure (70/22) and pulse (52, light and hard to find). EMS arrived soon after and at that point patient felt much better. EMS decided not to transport the patient to the ER. They instructed patient to follow up with his provider. Patient left the vaccine area under his own power about half an hour later.

Close
Patient received Janssen COVID19 vaccine (LOT#201A21A) in his left arm at approximately 14:43 on 5/25/21. During the 15 minute observation period, he expressed "I don't feel well" and endorsed dizziness/ lightheadedness, slight tingling feeling in fingers, and nausea. Shortly thereafter at approximately 14:50, he started to slouch and appeared faint while sitting in a chair with eyes closed. He did not fall or hit any part of his body. He was easily aroused with a touch on his arm and responded to verbal questions immediately. He denied trouble breathing, chest pain, palpitations, headache, muscle weakness, vision changes, skin reactions, swelling. He was oriented x3 and not exhibiting verbal or swallowing problems. His vitals were normal- HR 80 bpm and BP 105/80 mmHg. He was offered a receptacle to vomit in if needed; however, he did not vomit. This initial reaction was consistent with potential vasovagal reaction/ near-syncope after vaccination. Patient was encouraged and instructed to sit on the floor to prevent injury in case of fall but he refused. Staff offered him water, a fan, and opened windows while monitoring. Later while waiting for a ride at around 15:10, he endorsed headache (first above his eyes and then toward the back of his head) and clarified this did not feel like a typical migraine that he has had before. Then at around 15:20 he endorsed vision changes in his right eye- he could not see a portion of vision out of that eye except peripheral vision and described not being able to see writing on the right side of a whiteboard in front of him in the room. Later he described a resolution of that gap in vision but then had blurry vision out of that eye. He denied any vision changes in the left eye. Due to alarming symptoms of vision changes and onset of headache, patient was recommended to go to ER for further observation and evaluation. He was not in urgent distress and patient did not wish for EMS to be called but agreed to go to ER when his emergency contact picked him up. Patient's emergency contact came to pick up patient at approximately 15:40 and was recommended to take him to the ER. Patient and emergency contact were amenable to this plan. He was able to stand up and walk to the car without issues.

Client received the COVID vaccine Janssen Lot#205A21A at 1:29 PM. RN was alerted by the client's family prior to vaccination that the client has a history of "fainting" with injections. RN recommended vaccination on the cot in the observation area to decrease risk of syncope. The client and his parents refused vaccination in the observation area and his mother stated "if he can look at his phone he'll be fine." The client received the vaccination at the table and ambulated to the observation area. RN was alerted by the client's parents at 1:39 and responded. EMT also responded at this time. The client was not verbally responsive to RN and EMT and his posture was tense sitting in the chair. RN elevated the client's legs on a metal chair. The client's posture relaxed and subsequently the client regained responsiveness. No injury was sustained. The client then stated that he was dizzy and lightheaded. He denied SOB, throat tightening, and itching. . Client was AOx4. Vitals obtained by EMT were as follows: BP 132/88 and HR 64 regular rate and rhythm. RN noted pallor on the client's face. At 1:42PM the client stated he was "a little bit dizzy" denied any other s/s of an allergic reaction. The client was offered water and began drinking it. No medications administered. Client denied any chronic conditions or medications and no known allergies. He began eating some goldfish at 1:45 PM. RN provided education to client and his parents regarding s/s of anaphylaxis, when to seek EMS, to follow up with PCP regarding syncope event, and V-safe. The client and his parents voiced understanding of this. Vitals obtained by EMT at 1:50 were BP 122/90, HR 72, RR 20. Repeat vitals obtained at 2:00PM were BP 122/86, HR 64, and RR 16. The client departed the vaccination site at 2:05 with his parents unassisted with a steady gait. The client's parents drove him home.

The patient recovered from anaphylactic reaction (passing out/ could not breath/ swollen lips and face) on MAY-2021, and was recovering from fever, and lips were drooping to the right side of face. This report was serious (Other Medically Important Condition, and Life Threatening).; Sender's Comments: V0: 20210532244-COVID-19 VACCINE AD26.COV2.S-ANAPHYLACTIC REACTION. Patient had an initial response 2 days after the vaccine, with general malaise, dry mouth, headache and itching hands as well as local discomfort at the injection site that seemed to resolve spontaneously. On April 3rd he had non-specific changes in his hands that he attributed to cold weather that led to discomfort when running them under warm water. By monday APril 5th he was having worsening sensitivity in his hands and feet to heat, touch and experienced numbness. he also began to have difficulty walking. He went to the ER April 6th and was discharged April 7th after undergoing MRI of the brain and spinal cord, labs and lumbar puncture, with a presumptive diagnosis of early Guillain-barre Syndrome. His symptoms continued to worse, loss of gait was more pronounced as well as loss of balance and new off sensations in his tongue. He was admitted to the hospital, continued to undergo diagnostic workout. Results from tests on APril 6th came back positive for Anti nuclear antibodies and high protein in his CSF. He was treated with 3 days of infused Immunoglobolin therapy and was discharged on April 11th with a diagnosis of likely GBS. His symptoms continue to worsen slightly, but with less day to day decline

24 2021-04-13 feeling hot, weakness, feeling cold (Saturday)When I came home after I received the vaccine I didn't really have anything to do, so I de... Read more
Close
(Saturday)When I came home after I received the vaccine I didn't really have anything to do, so I decided to take a nap and rest. I think after I woke up is when I started to feel the side effects. I can't remember exactly but I started feeling cold. I didn't think too much of it I just thought it was a cold day (which was quickly turning to night). Later that night I started feelinga bit dizzy and my head was hot but I still had chills. Since I had a had a blanket with me, and I think I was starting to feel what would become muscle aches, I just didn't want to move from the couch to my room. Feeling chills the rest of the night, I realized it was bad choice, since one of my family members left a window open. The cold air of the night really exacerbated my chills. Despite the cold I was still able to sleep, but the next day (Sunday) I did have a slight cough which I think was from experiencing the cold air of the night and not a side effect from the vaccine. (Sunday) This is when I really felt all the side effects. I felt weak, chills, headache, dizziness, muscle aches,(I'm not sure if I had a fever, I couldn't think clearly my head felt hot). I haven't had a hangover but I think that is what it would feel like to have one. I basically slept most of day Sunday ; This time in my room with 3 blankets (light blankets )and heat up (felt like 80°F under blankets). I was sweating under the blankets but it really helped warm me up and alleviate my chills. I woke up later that day to a call to help my sister with some work. I couldn't drive, felt weak and dehydrated(dark orange/yellow pee), but she insisted so she picked me up and scolded me for not eating anything all day(besides the side effects I mention, I think I may have also lost my appetite because I felt dizzy). I was still feeling my head aching after I woke up, still had muscle aches and a slight cough too. It was raining that day so I put on a winter coat with layers underneath to help with my chills. At her home she gave me a Gatorade (and water) which I think really helped since I was sweating a lot under the blankets when I fell asleep. She also gave me some home cooked meals she made. The combination of drinks, food, and familial concern really helped me recover. By Monday my cough was gone and the side effects had worn off to the point that I could go to work safely. My mother & father also received vaccine at the same time I got it. My father also experienced side effects but his started later with the most effects felt on Tuesday. My mother did not get any side effects.

Patient received the vaccine at approximately 10am on 6/21/21. Shortly after receiving the vaccine, he complained of a headache and arm pain. Patient was told to remain seated and was monitored by pharmacist and staff. After 20 minutes, he was still not feeling well. He was moved into a different observation area. Based on symptoms it appeared he was having a a vasovagal reaction. He did not want to lie down and elevate his feet. At approximately 1/2 hour, he became nauseous and threw up. We continued to monitor him. He still had a headache and said he felt off. He had no swelling in the face and was speaking without issue. No hives were noticed. Patient said he was having a hard time breathing- I suggested he remove his mask to get more fresh air. After removing the mask, he said it felt better to breathe. In total, patient was monitored for 3 hours. He did not lose conscience, exhibit facial swelling or hives. Patient went back to work for 1 hour then left to go home. Prior to receiving the shot, patient showed a lot of anxiety and was hesitant to get vaccine. In the end, he decided he wanted to get it. Per medical staff at his work, he does tend to be high stressed and anxious. I followed up with patient on 6/22/21. He stated that he was feeling a lot better. He did have redness at the injection site- I explained he could ice the area. He still had a headache= I instructed him he could take a pain reliever. He mentioned he had a purple spot on his back. I asked if he had any other spots and said he would have to check. I suggested he contact his PCP and make an appointment to be seen.

25 2021-04-12 pain in extremity One week after receiving the Johnson & Johnson vaccine, several small bruises (6-8) appeared on the ... Read more
Close
One week after receiving the Johnson & Johnson vaccine, several small bruises (6-8) appeared on the back of my left leg. Throughout the day, my leg developed a soreness that, after reading a 10 Feb 2021 story in the newspaper about COVID vaccine recipients developing immune thrombocytopenia caused me to seek medical treatment in the afternoon of 4/6/2020. I first visited an urgent care facility where my high blood pressure (130/98) combined with my slight lightheadedness, soreness in the leg and observes bruising were enough for the tending physician to recommend rushing to the ER for bloodwork to be performed immediately. I was admitted to the ER in the early evening with an elevated blood pressure (~150/111) and the bruising still prevalent. The tending nurse practitioner authorized a complete blood count (CBC) and discharged me an hour later when the results came back ?extremely close to normal,? noting that my platelet count of 194 was no immediate cause for concern. Since then, the bruising and soreness has subsided.

25 2021-06-20 unresponsive to stimuli Last week Monday - June 14 I worked 1pm-9pm. My opening pharmacist left around I'd say 2pm, or 2:15p... Read more
Close
Last week Monday - June 14 I worked 1pm-9pm. My opening pharmacist left around I'd say 2pm, or 2:15pm~ish and hadn't witnessed the incident. So somewhere around that approximate time I was inside the pharmacy working on a back computer by drive thru and I heard someone yell for help in the waiting area. It was the kind of help you just know means something really drastic has just occurred. I quickly entered the waiting area via the pharmacy consultation door and saw patient face down between two chairs and his nose had a consistent drip of blood that was apparent on the floor. My technician who was in the consultation room told me he had received a Johnson and Johnson Covid vaccine probably within 5 minutes of the incident. With the combination of that information and the visualization of an active bleed, I made eye contact with another staff member inside the pharmacy at will call and told him to call 911 which he turned around immediately and did. The man was alone, but the woman who yelled for help was also calling 911 I believe. At this point I'd say approximately every 3 seconds, a new drop of blood would emerge. There were a couple people nearby including the customer and I asked everyone to stay back a little, I surveyed the scene and it appeared to be safe and I approached patient as I tried to verbally get a response of some sort. I asked if he could hear me, if he knew where he was and what happened, both with no response. The bystander recommended turning him on his side but with the unknown cause of the bleed and the recent vaccination I didn't know if it could be CNS or spinal related and since we were on the phone with EMS, we could get their recommendation of whether to move him or not. Within 15-30 seconds probably, he started regaining consciousness and he was scared at first and rightfully so. He jolted up and back and looked at me like, "why am I face down in my own blood (and probably in a lot of pain i'm sure)", and it scared me a little to be honest. I told him what we had observed, and I saw the bridge of his nose stuck out beyond what was normal but I'm not sure what normal is to him..?? I saw two small lacerations on the side of his nose and a pair of glasses on the floor. I couldn't determine if they were broken or not but surmised, he must have fainted and fallen off the chair and landed on his glasses which cut and may have even broken his nose. Or maybe the ground broke his nose. Either way it looked bad. There were several store team members around at this point (those listed in this report), and the patient was given paper towels for the bleeding and bottled water. There was a store use wheelchair we put him in when he was ready and wheeled him into the consultation room where he could be monitored until EMS arrived. While speaking with the patient before EMS arrived, he rendered all the following information: Never had a reaction to a vaccine before Never had any knowledge of high or low BP issues Doesn't recall ever feeling lightheaded or dizzy upon quickly erecting Might have low blood sugar issues Reasonings for the above response: Hadn't eaten that day yet before his shot and was feeling a little anxious about it Last time he gave blood he hadn't eaten breakfast and passed out after that This was the only other fainting history mentioned He did say it was within the last 6 months EMS arrived within another 2-3 minutes I'd say at which time we had already began the cleaning process. We blocked off the area to other customers, we halted the vaccination process until the issue was resolved, I printed the Biohazard Spill procedures, we obtained the bio-hazard spill kit, and proceeded to clean with all the PPE and sanitization materials included within the kit. After the entire process was completed the store team even ran the cleaner over the area to go above and beyond. The patient refused the ride to the hospital via ambulance due to costs and signed a medical waiver I believe..??

Close
Patient received the Jansen covid-19 vaccine today. he was fine when he received the vaccine but when he was sitting in the chair in the pharmacy lobby he fainted. I saw him fall out of chair and immediately ran out the door to assist him. He fell out of chair face down on the floor. When I reached him I rolled him over and spoke to him and he responded to me. I had him remain on the floor for several minutes before I had him sit in the chair. He bit his lip and there was a spot of blood and he hit his forehead on the floor. We called emergency number and emergency medical team arrived shortly and took his vital signs and they were normal. He was a little clammy and sweating a little. I gave him a bottle of cold water to drink while he was sitting. The emergency team checked him out and they ask him if he wanted to go to hospital and he declined going. The emergency medical team left and I had him wait a while longer. I had him call his mother to come and pick him up so he did not have to drive himself. His mother arrived about 20 minutes later and I went over with her what had happened. She took him home and I called to check on him after a few hours and he said he was doing fine. He also stated while talking with him that he had never passed out when getting other vaccines or the flu shots previously. He did state that he didn't like needles but was not afraid to get the vaccine.

After his vaccination, patient was waiting 15 minutes in waiting room. Patient knocked on door and said he didn't feel well. I closed door and turned to grab epi-pen and diphenhydramine. When I turned back around, patient fell on the floor and was unresponsive. I asked my technician to call 911. Patient regained consciousness in about 10 seconds and I told him an ambulance was coming. I observed his breathing to be normal. He sat up against the wall in a cold sweat and told me this has happened to him one time when he donated blood. The ambulance and paramedic arrived very promptly. They took him to the ambulance.

LOST CONSCIOUSNESS; COLD TO THE TOUCH; SWEATY; This spontaneous report received from a consumer concerned a 25 year old male. The patient's weight was 68 kilograms, and height was 170 centimeters. No past medical history or concurrent conditions were reported. The patient experienced drug allergy when treated with azithromycin. The patient received covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, route of admin not reported, and batch number: 206A21A expiry: UNKNOWN) dose was not reported, 1 total administered on 07-JUL-2021 to left arm for prophylactic vaccination. No concomitant medications were reported. On 07-JUL-2021, few minutes after the vaccination, the patient lost consciousness and regained it a minute later. The patient was also cold to the touch and sweaty. The patient had visited the doctor/healthcare professional office. The action taken with covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s was not applicable. The patient recovered from lost consciousness, cold to the touch, and sweaty on 07-JUL-2021. This report was serious (Other Medically Important Condition).; Sender's Comments: V0:20210718535- covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s-Lost consciousness. This event(s) is considered un-assessable. The event(s) has a compatible/suggestive temporal relationship, is unlabeled, and has unknown scientific plausibility. There is no information on any other factors potentially associated with the event(s).
